MAN: d She's the girl l'll marry, marry, marry

262
00:36:40,083 --> 00:36:42,999
d She's the girl for me

263
00:36:43,166 --> 00:36:45,124
d Oh, she's the girl l'll...

264
00:36:45,291 --> 00:36:47,374
Whoa there, Nelly. Whoa.

265
00:37:16,708 --> 00:37:18,790
(Horse and cart approaching)

266
00:37:29,583 --> 00:37:31,665
Whoa!

267
00:37:35,708 --> 00:37:37,999
Dear God, teach him not to think.

268
00:37:40,166 --> 00:37:44,040
Help him to accept things as they are.
Don't let him question things.

269
00:37:45,083 --> 00:37:47,040
Not too much.

270
00:37:47,208 --> 00:37:48,624
Handsome bit of work.

271
00:37:48,791 --> 00:37:53,082
You'd have to get yourself a new pair of britches
before you could sit on one of them.

272
00:37:53,250 --> 00:37:55,832
- What's his asking price?
- A pound apiece.

273
00:37:56,916 --> 00:37:58,999
Know how long it takes him?

274
00:37:59,833 --> 00:38:02,332
Two weeks a chair. Getting on.

275
00:38:06,250 --> 00:38:09,374
What would you say
to your trying to up the price a bit?

276
00:38:10,916 --> 00:38:12,999
l'll take full responsibility.

277
00:38:14,333 --> 00:38:16,415
- l could ask.
- Good man.

278
00:38:18,166 --> 00:38:20,249
l'll to the top of the hill with you.

279
00:38:22,875 --> 00:38:24,415
Walk on.

280
00:38:26,958 --> 00:38:29,040
Up you go, go on!

281
00:38:48,916 --> 00:38:51,457
(Young woman sobs)
OLDER WOMAN: Come.

282
00:38:51,625 --> 00:38:53,707
Come to me.

283
00:38:59,333 --> 00:39:01,415
l'm not angry with you.

284
00:39:08,500 --> 00:39:11,499
You see, if we get
something for nothing in this world,

285
00:39:11,666 --> 00:39:14,040
it means someone else may have to suffer.

286
00:39:17,041 --> 00:39:19,124
Now, that's not a good thing, is it?

287
00:39:25,833 --> 00:39:27,915
lt's quite simple really, you know.

288
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:31,999
We only have to love one another
to know what we must do.

289
00:39:50,583 --> 00:39:53,707
Forgive Charity, she meant no harm.

290
00:40:09,125 --> 00:40:11,207
He's a good lad.

291
00:40:18,083 --> 00:40:20,165
But not perfect.

292
00:40:28,083 --> 00:40:30,707
Has his ups and downs, just like the rest of us.

293
00:40:35,750 --> 00:40:37,290
But...

294
00:40:40,875 --> 00:40:43,415
..he's been a good son to me.

295
00:40:46,416 --> 00:40:48,499
Who'd have sons?

296
00:41:20,791 --> 00:41:22,874
(Giggles)

297
00:41:26,833 --> 00:41:28,915
What's funny?

298
00:41:34,750 --> 00:41:36,707
Now, get you back.

299
00:41:36,875 --> 00:41:38,957
You can't come wi' us.

300
00:41:42,875 --> 00:41:44,957
Go on, get you back.

301
00:42:16,916 --> 00:42:18,999
(Women laughing)

302
00:43:27,541 --> 00:43:31,665
d A poor man to labour, believe me, 'tis so

303
00:43:31,833 --> 00:43:36,290
d To maintain his family is willing to go

304
00:43:36,458 --> 00:43:38,624
d Either hedging or ditching

305
00:43:38,791 --> 00:43:40,915
d To plough or to reap

306
00:43:41,083 --> 00:43:45,540
d But how does he live
on eight shillings a week?

307
00:43:45,708 --> 00:43:50,082
d Eight shillings a week, eight shillings a week

308
00:43:50,250 --> 00:43:54,707
d But how does he live
on eight shillings a week?

309
00:43:54,875 --> 00:43:59,624
d So now to conclude and to finish my song

310
00:43:59,791 --> 00:44:04,124
d May the times be much better
before it's too long

311
00:44:04,291 --> 00:44:13,249
d May every labourer be able to keep
his children and wife on 12 shillings a week

312
00:44:43,583 --> 00:44:45,540
(Women laughing)

313
00:44:45,708 --> 00:44:47,790
(Man singing)

314
00:45:23,916 --> 00:45:25,999
(Woman whispers) James.

315
00:46:00,583 --> 00:46:02,665
James.

316
00:46:04,958 --> 00:46:07,040
l'm not going back there.

317
00:46:07,958 --> 00:46:10,040
No.

318
00:46:19,541 --> 00:46:21,624
James.

319
00:46:22,666 --> 00:46:24,749
You must come to bed.

320
00:46:54,541 --> 00:47:16,790
d Sailor's Hornpipe

321
00:48:13,708 --> 00:48:15,790
(Cheering)

322
00:48:31,416 --> 00:48:38,499
Roll up, roll up! For don't you know,
it's Sergeant Bell and his Royal Raree Show.

323
00:48:38,666 --> 00:48:42,082
Highly instructive for lads and lasses.

324
00:48:42,250 --> 00:48:44,915
ldeal for the gentry and the labouring classes.

325
00:48:45,083 --> 00:48:48,165
Come on, now, don't hog it.
Let the lady in, there we are.

326
00:48:48,333 --> 00:48:50,290
There's a man of God.

327
00:48:50,458 --> 00:48:52,415
l've the very thing for you, sir.

328
00:48:52,583 --> 00:48:56,040
Jacob and Adam in the land of Nod.

329
00:48:56,208 --> 00:49:00,874
Now, it's only a penny to take a look,
to see the pictures from the holy book.

330
00:49:01,041 --> 00:49:02,999
Oh, sir, l beg your pardon,

331
00:49:03,166 --> 00:49:05,665
it's Eve without her clothes on,

332
00:49:05,833 --> 00:49:07,915
in the garden! Ha-ha-ha!

333
00:49:09,000 --> 00:49:12,999
Roll up, Sergeant Bell's Raree Show!

334
00:49:13,166 --> 00:49:15,124
Only a penny to see the view.

335
00:49:15,291 --> 00:49:19,790
See Nelson being defeated
at the Battle of Waterloo.

336
00:49:19,958 --> 00:49:23,540
The Raree Show's the thing
for all the lads and the lasses,

337
00:49:23,708 --> 00:49:27,957
but be careful, thou young titches,
not to breathe on the glasses.

338
00:49:28,125 --> 00:49:30,207
d Lively fiddle and whistle

339
00:50:24,375 --> 00:50:26,457
(Chatter and laughter)

340
00:50:29,166 --> 00:50:31,249
John. John.

341
00:50:32,625 --> 00:50:34,707
(Grunts)

342
00:51:17,541 --> 00:51:19,624
FOREMAN: Ford!

343
00:51:22,333 --> 00:51:24,415
Grey.

344
00:51:28,833 --> 00:51:30,915
Hammett.

345
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:34,207
Father. Father.

346
00:51:34,375 --> 00:51:37,457
- Leave me alone, son. Leave me alone!
- Father.

347
00:51:37,625 --> 00:51:39,707
l'm tired!

348
00:51:56,375 --> 00:51:57,874
(Low conversations)

349
00:51:58,041 --> 00:52:02,124
- We've talked about this before.
- But we've got the advantage now.

350
00:52:13,583 --> 00:52:16,582
MAN lN BACKGROUND:
l'm not saying we should go against the law.

351
00:52:16,750 --> 00:52:19,082
l'm saying we've had enough of all this.

352
00:53:58,416 --> 00:54:00,499
No!

353
00:54:56,916 --> 00:54:58,999
(Woman screams in agony)

354
00:55:00,500 --> 00:55:02,624
Tom!

355
00:55:02,791 --> 00:55:04,874
Argh!

356
00:55:11,625 --> 00:55:13,957
JOHN: lf mother was alive
to see what you've become!

357
00:55:14,125 --> 00:55:17,749
JAMES: Leave our mother out of this.
- There's such a thing as responsibility.

358
00:55:17,916 --> 00:55:22,124
JAMES: What's so responsible about fathering
a child when you can't make ends meet?

359
00:55:22,291 --> 00:55:24,249
Who do you think you are telling me what to do?

360
00:55:24,416 --> 00:55:26,374
Your brother, that's who.

361
00:55:26,541 --> 00:55:28,999
My first loyalty is to Bridget and the baby.

362
00:55:29,166 --> 00:55:32,082
You want me out of the way now. ls that it?

363
00:55:32,250 --> 00:55:37,249
- That's a good idea. There's the road.
- l'm boss in my life, not you or anyone else.

364
00:55:37,416 --> 00:55:40,582
l'll decide what l want to do
where and when l want to do it.

365
00:55:40,750 --> 00:55:43,374
That bloody baby has gone right to your head.

366
00:55:55,958 --> 00:55:58,040
(Baby stirs)

367
00:56:01,250 --> 00:56:03,332
(Baby grizzles)

368
00:56:04,500 --> 00:56:09,415
Shh.

369
00:56:35,291 --> 00:56:37,374
(Sheep bleating)

370
00:56:43,208 --> 00:56:45,332
What on earth is it?

371
00:56:45,500 --> 00:56:47,749
lt's a skeleton, Mrs Wetham.

372
00:56:49,750 --> 00:56:51,665
But what's it for?

373
00:56:51,833 --> 00:56:53,915
lt's a design for a banner.

374
00:56:55,000 --> 00:56:58,707
- For a union.
- Union?

375
00:57:00,625 --> 00:57:02,749
A society of friends.

376
00:57:03,833 --> 00:57:06,374
lt's a most unusual request.

377
00:57:06,541 --> 00:57:11,082
- We'll pay a fair price.
- l'll speak with my husband.

378
00:57:26,125 --> 00:57:27,665
MAN: Mr Loveless.

379
00:57:29,791 --> 00:57:31,874
Good day.

380
00:57:34,250 --> 00:57:36,207
Well, well, well,

381
00:57:36,375 --> 00:57:38,957
what brings you into town?

382
00:57:40,125 --> 00:57:44,207
l thought l detected a...Tolpiddle hereabouts.

383
00:57:45,750 --> 00:57:51,040
So you're a lover of prints.
Who would have guessed it?

384
00:57:51,208 --> 00:57:53,290
l like to extend my mind whenever l can.

385
00:57:53,458 --> 00:57:59,290
How rewarding that one who uses his hands...
might also use his mind.

386
00:58:03,041 --> 00:58:06,499
An antidote to the sloth of countrifying,
Mr Frampton.

387
00:58:08,041 --> 00:58:11,499
The problem, Mr Loveless, is to match it.

388
00:58:13,125 --> 00:58:18,665
And having matched it,
to use both hand and mind

389
00:58:18,833 --> 00:58:21,624
to exert it to some use.

390
00:58:22,458 --> 00:58:25,249
For a well-balanced appetite,

391
00:58:25,416 --> 00:58:29,832
we must satisfy all our parts.

392
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:32,082
Eh, Mr Loveless?

393
00:58:34,458 --> 00:58:40,165
But it is sad to see folk who are...
blind to their own interests.

394
00:58:41,208 --> 00:58:43,290
Folk are not blind, sir.

395
00:58:44,000 --> 00:58:48,457
- But it is those that master us that cannot see.
- Explain yourself, Loveless.

396
00:58:54,125 --> 00:58:56,207
Here, for instance.

397
00:58:57,291 --> 00:58:59,249
Can you see this, sir?

398
00:58:59,416 --> 00:59:01,499
Yes.

399
00:59:09,125 --> 00:59:11,249
Can you see it now?

400
00:59:12,333 --> 00:59:14,082
No.

401
00:59:15,166 --> 00:59:17,249
What prevents you seeing it?

402
00:59:18,333 --> 00:59:20,374
The silver, of course.

403
00:59:20,541 --> 00:59:22,624
That's just it.

404
00:59:23,708 --> 00:59:25,790
Sir.

405
00:59:29,375 --> 00:59:31,457
GEORGE: Mr Pitt.

406
00:59:33,041 --> 00:59:36,249
- George Loveless.
- lt's very kind of you to meet me, sir.

407
00:59:36,416 --> 00:59:40,040
- l thought we'd take a ride out of town.
- Thank you, sir.

408
00:59:57,333 --> 00:59:59,415
(Wind blusters)

409
01:00:25,791 --> 01:00:27,874
(Trumpet fanfare)

410
01:00:29,125 --> 01:00:31,040
(Gunfire)

411
01:00:37,708 --> 01:00:39,790
(Shouts angrily under cacophony)

412
01:00:54,250 --> 01:00:56,332
(Trumpet, drumming, xylophone)

413
01:01:22,958 --> 01:01:25,957
Do you want to buy a ticket to see the show, sir?

414
01:01:26,125 --> 01:01:28,082
None of us needs to bother with that.

415
01:01:28,250 --> 01:01:31,249
We'll be having a battle of our own
soon enough. For nowt.

416
01:01:31,416 --> 01:01:36,415
My dear sir, l think you underestimate
the novelty of this unique exhibition.

417
01:01:36,583 --> 01:01:39,915
A diorama is the highest achievement
of human ingenuity,

418
01:01:40,083 --> 01:01:46,665
delineating the most interesting parts of
the world in varying aspects of light and shade.

419
01:01:46,833 --> 01:01:50,082
How about a trip
to the other side of the world tomorrow?

420
01:01:52,000 --> 01:01:55,082
What you offer, sir, is illusion.

421
01:01:56,083 --> 01:01:58,165
lt's the real world l'd like to see.

422
01:02:00,625 --> 01:02:03,374
ln our short lives we move about so little...

423
01:02:04,458 --> 01:02:06,832
..see so little.

424
01:02:09,750 --> 01:02:11,832
Yes.

425
01:02:13,125 --> 01:02:15,207
l'd like to travel one day.

426
01:02:18,708 --> 01:02:20,790
Hello, George.

427
01:03:11,750 --> 01:03:14,290
You're gonna have 25 children.

428
01:03:17,500 --> 01:03:22,457
lf you spent less time thinking about yourself
and more time helping others.

429
01:03:30,375 --> 01:03:32,332
l mean it.

430
01:03:32,500 --> 01:03:36,582
For your own good.
Getting on with a job never hurt no-one.

431
01:03:38,291 --> 01:03:40,374
Are you getting paid for it?

432
01:03:41,458 --> 01:03:43,415
ls he?

433
01:03:43,583 --> 01:03:45,540
Only a fool does something for nothing.

434
01:03:45,708 --> 01:03:50,082
Those men paid a shilling out of their
hard-earned money to join the union.

435
01:03:51,166 --> 01:03:53,707
lf you and others like you were to join...

436
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:13,749
He believes in what he's doing.

437
01:04:21,208 --> 01:04:23,165
Don't worry about me.

438
01:04:23,333 --> 01:04:24,999
l can look after myself.

439
01:04:32,541 --> 01:04:34,624
(Gentle knocking)

440
01:04:36,416 --> 01:04:39,207
MAN: Who comes here to disturb
the peace and harmony

441
01:04:39,375 --> 01:04:41,457
of this our most worthy and honourable order?

442
01:04:41,625 --> 01:04:43,874
l'm a brother with strangers.

443
01:04:44,041 --> 01:04:47,832
We wish to be admitted into this,
your most worthy and honourable order.

444
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:50,999
Most worthy brothers,
another stands at the door with strangers

445
01:04:51,166 --> 01:04:55,332
who wish to be admitted into this,
our most worthy and honourable order...

446
01:04:55,500 --> 01:04:57,582
OLD TOM: Let them enter.

447
01:05:23,000 --> 01:05:25,082
(Floorboard creaks)

448
01:05:27,958 --> 01:05:30,207
(Muffled men's voices)

449
01:05:37,875 --> 01:05:39,957
Dear God, help them.

450
01:05:43,000 --> 01:05:45,082
(Soft footsteps upstairs)

451
01:05:51,000 --> 01:05:55,332
Strangers within our secret walls,

452
01:05:56,416 --> 01:06:04,874
we have admitted you
hoping you will prove honest, faithful and true.

453
01:06:05,041 --> 01:06:08,415
lf you cannot keep the secrets we require,

454
01:06:08,583 --> 01:06:10,540
go hence,

455
01:06:10,708 --> 01:06:12,790
you are at liberty to retire.

456
01:06:13,833 --> 01:06:15,790
Are your motives pure?

457
01:06:15,958 --> 01:06:17,332
Yes.

458
01:06:19,458 --> 01:06:27,290
Then amongst us you will shortly be
entitled to the endearing name of 'brother'.

459
01:06:27,458 --> 01:06:30,957
And what you hear or see here done,

460
01:06:31,125 --> 01:06:34,540
you must not disclose to any other.

461
01:06:35,583 --> 01:06:39,415
We are uniting to cultivate friendship,

462
01:06:39,583 --> 01:06:42,415
as well as to protect our trade,

463
01:06:43,125 --> 01:06:47,874
and due respect must to all our laws be paid.

464
01:06:48,041 --> 01:06:50,665
Are your motives pure?

465
01:06:50,833 --> 01:06:52,915
Yes.

466
01:06:59,750 --> 01:07:02,207
Give the strangers sight.

467
01:07:11,708 --> 01:07:13,540
Strangers,

468
01:07:13,708 --> 01:07:15,790
mark well this shadow...

469
01:07:16,791 --> 01:07:18,832
..which you see.

470
01:07:19,541 --> 01:07:21,999
lt is a faithful emblem...

471
01:07:22,166 --> 01:07:24,415
of man's destiny.

472
01:07:42,666 --> 01:07:44,624
Strangers,

473
01:07:44,791 --> 01:07:46,874
you are welcome.

474
01:07:47,875 --> 01:07:49,999
And if you prove sincere,

475
01:07:50,166 --> 01:07:53,332
you'll not repent your pains and labour here.

476
01:07:54,583 --> 01:07:57,290
We have one common interest,

477
01:07:58,333 --> 01:08:00,415
and one common soul,

478
01:08:01,208 --> 01:08:06,540
which should by virtue
guide and actuate the whole.

479
01:08:10,583 --> 01:08:16,790
The design of this, our order, is love and unity,

480
01:08:16,958 --> 01:08:20,874
with self protection
founded on the laws of equity.

481
01:08:22,458 --> 01:08:25,165
And when you have
our mystic rites gone through,

482
01:08:26,041 --> 01:08:28,832
our secrets all will be disclosed to you.

483
01:08:47,791 --> 01:08:51,624
Edward Legg, do you swear to this alliance?

484
01:09:00,666 --> 01:09:02,707
EDWARD: I swear.

485
01:09:02,875 --> 01:09:06,665
GEORGE: And now,
shouldst thou ever pro?e deceitful,

486
01:09:07,750 --> 01:09:09,832
remember thine end.

487
01:09:11,333 --> 01:09:13,415
Remember.

488
01:09:21,250 --> 01:09:27,540
VICAR: l like to think of myself
as being a friend to all men.

489
01:09:31,208 --> 01:09:36,457
lndeed it's flattering
that you should ask me to intervene, but...

490
01:09:38,291 --> 01:09:43,957
..don't you think
you've got things slightly out of proportion?

491
01:09:46,083 --> 01:09:48,165
Difficult times, Vicar.

492
01:09:49,750 --> 01:09:51,832
Mr Frampton...

493
01:09:52,750 --> 01:09:55,290
..has not been ungenerous.

494
01:09:56,666 --> 01:09:58,874
As you can see.

495
01:10:17,666 --> 01:10:21,082
Mr Frampton says for you
to make yourselves comfortable.

496
01:10:48,500 --> 01:10:50,582
(Men conversing within)

497
01:10:57,333 --> 01:10:59,415
(Muffled men's voices)

498
01:11:07,125 --> 01:11:09,207
(Men laugh in another room)

499
01:11:37,208 --> 01:11:39,165
(Applause in another room)

500
01:11:39,333 --> 01:11:41,415
(Laughter)

501
01:11:49,125 --> 01:11:51,082
Good afternoon, gentlemen.

502
01:11:51,250 --> 01:11:54,790
George, how very nice to see you.

503
01:11:56,416 --> 01:11:58,582
l do hope we haven't kept you waiting.

504
01:11:59,666 --> 01:12:02,749
We had no idea of the time.
Please accept my apologies.

505
01:12:02,916 --> 01:12:04,874
Gentlemen, please...

506
01:12:05,041 --> 01:12:07,124
sit down.

507
01:12:13,250 --> 01:12:15,332
FRAMPTON: Please sit down.

508
01:12:26,416 --> 01:12:31,290
Well, gentlemen,
how good it is to see you all here.

509
01:12:31,458 --> 01:12:36,457
l must claim, in all modesty, to be a fair man.

510
01:12:36,625 --> 01:12:41,165
Mr Frampton, my friends asked me to act
as independent spokesman on their behalf.

511
01:12:41,333 --> 01:12:43,290
Yes, yes, yes, yes.

512
01:12:43,458 --> 01:12:46,457
l see no reason to detain you
longer than is necessary.

513
01:12:46,625 --> 01:12:48,582
The vicar has put your case.

514
01:12:48,750 --> 01:12:50,915
And we must admire his ability to see...

515
01:12:51,083 --> 01:12:53,457
both sides of the coin.

516
01:12:53,625 --> 01:12:56,290
(Chuckles)

517
01:13:07,250 --> 01:13:09,082
We felt the time has come...

518
01:13:09,250 --> 01:13:13,374
Yes, of course you did.
We have your best interests at heart.

519
01:13:13,541 --> 01:13:19,874
lt's just that...well, we don't know where we are
what with the wages going down week by week.

520
01:13:20,041 --> 01:13:22,749
You're quite right. There's no question of that.

521
01:13:22,916 --> 01:13:28,665
But in spite of the circumstances, and with,
if l might add, a fervent hope for the future,

522
01:13:28,833 --> 01:13:32,499
an extra shilling will be granted.

523
01:13:35,583 --> 01:13:38,624
Are you saying eight shillings?

524
01:13:38,791 --> 01:13:40,874
Eight!

525
01:13:44,958 --> 01:13:47,332
Have you any more questions, gentlemen?

526
01:14:07,958 --> 01:14:10,040
(Man belches)

527
01:14:24,541 --> 01:14:26,624
Have away, Nelly.

528
01:14:31,666 --> 01:14:33,749
(Bells ring at various pitches)

529
01:14:40,166 --> 01:14:42,624
Mr Frampton told me to give this to you.

530
01:14:42,791 --> 01:14:45,790
EDWARD: Thank you very much, miss.
That's very kind of you.

531
01:14:48,333 --> 01:14:50,874
Thank you very much, miss. Thank you.

532
01:14:51,041 --> 01:14:52,957
That's all right, Mr Legg.

533
01:15:10,708 --> 01:15:12,749
FOREMAN: Hammett.

534
01:15:17,041 --> 01:15:19,124
Legg.

535
01:15:25,958 --> 01:15:27,374
Look.

536
01:15:27,541 --> 01:15:29,624
Loveless.

537
01:15:50,791 --> 01:15:53,290
Come on, George.

538
01:15:53,458 --> 01:15:55,540
One must eat to live.

539
01:17:03,916 --> 01:17:05,999
Sing for us, Elvi.

540
01:17:08,916 --> 01:17:10,874
l'll sing for you. Come on, Briney.

541
01:17:11,041 --> 01:17:13,124
We'll sing for 'em.

542
01:17:15,083 --> 01:17:19,332
d When l was just a beardless boy
no more than six years old

543
01:17:19,500 --> 01:17:23,040
d l used to go akeeping crows
in rain and wind and cold

544
01:17:23,208 --> 01:17:26,624
d Oh, well do l remember now
as well as it can be

545
01:17:26,791 --> 01:17:28,749
d My little house...

546
01:17:28,916 --> 01:17:32,249
d ..thatched in the marsh agin the sea

547
01:17:32,416 --> 01:17:35,457
d Cahoo, cahoo, you old black crow

548
01:17:35,625 --> 01:17:38,749
d Go fly away to Sutton

549
01:17:38,916 --> 01:17:40,665
d lf you stop here twill cost you dear

550
01:17:40,833 --> 01:17:43,082
d l'll kill you dead as mutton

551
01:17:43,250 --> 01:17:45,707
(Laughter and applause)

552
01:17:45,875 --> 01:17:47,957
(Whispers)

553
01:17:50,791 --> 01:17:52,874
Shh.

554
01:17:59,125 --> 01:18:03,665
d lt's fare thee well, cold winter

555
01:18:03,833 --> 01:18:08,499
d And fare thee well, cold frost

556
01:18:09,291 --> 01:18:12,582
d Nothing have l gained

557
01:18:12,750 --> 01:18:17,582
d But my true love l've lost

558
01:18:17,750 --> 01:18:21,665
d l'll sing and l'll be merry

559
01:18:21,833 --> 01:18:26,165
d While a caution do l see

560
01:18:26,333 --> 01:18:30,790
d And l'll rest me when l'm weary

561
01:18:30,958 --> 01:18:35,582
d Let him go, farewell he

562
01:18:36,666 --> 01:18:40,665
d To half a pound of reason

563
01:18:40,833 --> 01:18:44,832
d Take a half a grain of sense

564
01:18:45,000 --> 01:18:48,624
d A small sprig of time

565
01:18:48,791 --> 01:18:53,040
d And as much of prudence

566
01:18:53,208 --> 01:18:57,165
d And mix them up together

567
01:18:57,333 --> 01:19:01,582
d As you may plainly see

568
01:19:01,750 --> 01:19:06,582
d l'll defy the lad for ever

569
01:19:06,750 --> 01:19:12,124
d Let him go, farewell he

570
01:19:17,000 --> 01:19:19,082
(Giggles)

571
01:19:32,458 --> 01:19:34,540
Poor Legg.

572
01:19:47,791 --> 01:19:49,874
(Hammering)

573
01:20:05,875 --> 01:20:08,582
Who's the next one
that we see in our galanty show?

574
01:20:08,750 --> 01:20:11,957
Why, it's three little soldier boys
standing in a row.

575
01:20:13,916 --> 01:20:16,207
Three little soldier boys.

576
01:20:16,375 --> 01:20:18,332
Standing at the battle.

577
01:20:18,500 --> 01:20:20,582
They hear the horses gallop.

578
01:20:22,708 --> 01:20:24,790
They hear the sabres rattle.

579
01:20:26,166 --> 01:20:29,499
Soon they'll wish that they were
safely tucked up in their beds.

580
01:20:29,666 --> 01:20:31,624
Because...bang goes the cannon!

581
01:20:31,791 --> 01:20:34,165
And off comes their heads!

582
01:20:53,708 --> 01:20:55,790
l'm a changed man, George.

583
01:20:56,875 --> 01:20:58,832
A reformed one.

584
01:20:59,000 --> 01:21:01,165
You swept the cobwebs out of my brain.

585
01:21:03,416 --> 01:21:05,832
l shall never forget Tolpiddle.

586
01:21:09,375 --> 01:21:11,040
Go, then,

587
01:21:11,208 --> 01:21:13,582
and make a union of lanternists.

588
01:21:33,958 --> 01:21:36,040
See?

589
01:21:37,416 --> 01:21:39,499
The heavens!

590
01:21:41,208 --> 01:21:43,290
Remember us!

591
01:21:44,333 --> 01:21:46,415
Remember!

592
01:21:55,583 --> 01:21:57,665
(Pounding on door)

593
01:22:41,833 --> 01:22:52,040
George Loveless?

594
01:22:55,583 --> 01:22:57,582
Yes.

595
01:24:06,625 --> 01:24:08,707
You're all right.

596
01:24:57,333 --> 01:25:01,415
PlTT: These Iabourers -
l use the word with the utmost respect -

597
01:25:01,583 --> 01:25:03,999
are worthy and honourable men.

598
01:25:04,166 --> 01:25:06,832
l've met George Loveless on several occasions.

599
01:25:07,000 --> 01:25:10,749
He is an honest man.
He told me the men work hard.

600
01:25:11,833 --> 01:25:16,040
These men have the right to a decent wage
for a decent job well done.

601
01:25:16,208 --> 01:25:18,332
Beyond this county,

602
01:25:18,500 --> 01:25:21,749
the wage of half a pound is tolerated.

603
01:25:23,375 --> 01:25:25,332
The solution is simple.

604
01:25:25,500 --> 01:25:31,165
A magistrate should fix the sum by law
as has always been the custom.

605
01:25:31,333 --> 01:25:33,290
l am a magistrate,

606
01:25:33,458 --> 01:25:37,249
Chairman of the Bench
and a member of the Grand Jury.

607
01:25:37,416 --> 01:25:42,582
Vicar, l understand that you were
an advocate for the Tolpiddle men.

608
01:25:42,750 --> 01:25:48,040
And that you were present when Mr Frampton
agreed to rectify their grievances.

609
01:25:48,208 --> 01:25:51,124
Were they not promised an extra shilling?

610
01:25:58,291 --> 01:25:59,832
Well?

611
01:26:01,041 --> 01:26:03,290
(Coughs)

612
01:26:03,458 --> 01:26:05,415
No.

613
01:26:05,583 --> 01:26:08,415
No such promise was made.

614
01:26:08,583 --> 01:26:10,540
Are you quite sure?

615
01:26:10,708 --> 01:26:12,665
He is a man of God!

616
01:26:12,833 --> 01:26:16,374
Mr Pitt, please don't make
such a fool of yourself!

617
01:26:16,541 --> 01:26:19,207
The men's wages are neither here nor there.

618
01:26:19,375 --> 01:26:22,040
They were engaged in secret meetings,

619
01:26:22,208 --> 01:26:24,165
administering illegal oaths,

620
01:26:24,333 --> 01:26:27,707
taking the law into their own hands,
and this must stop!

621
01:26:27,875 --> 01:26:32,207
PITT: We are talking about
a union of farm labourers.

622
01:26:32,375 --> 01:26:36,624
Which may be offensive to some
but is no longer against the law.

623
01:26:36,791 --> 01:26:40,540
All this nonsense about illegal oaths.
lt's a trumped-up charge.

624
01:26:40,708 --> 01:26:42,665
lt's on the statute book,

625
01:26:42,833 --> 01:26:44,707
Mr Pitt.

626
01:26:44,875 --> 01:26:46,832
You're a magistrate.

627
01:26:47,000 --> 01:26:49,915
l will tell you in the strictest confidence,

628
01:26:50,083 --> 01:26:53,790
l have it from no less a person
than the Home Sec...

629
01:26:53,958 --> 01:26:57,082
On the highest authority.

630
01:26:58,708 --> 01:27:00,790
This is the best way to proceed.

631
01:27:00,958 --> 01:27:04,665
We have followed every letter of the law.
Cautions were posted.

632
01:27:04,833 --> 01:27:11,415
Yes, two days before their arrest.
For an offence alleged as many months before.

633
01:27:11,583 --> 01:27:14,832
The men were charged before
Charles Wollaston.

634
01:27:15,000 --> 01:27:16,540
Your brother.

635
01:27:16,708 --> 01:27:18,457
Half-brother!

636
01:27:18,625 --> 01:27:20,374
Actually.

637
01:27:20,541 --> 01:27:23,665
William Ponsonby committed them
for trial at the assizes.

638
01:27:23,833 --> 01:27:26,624
- The Home Secretary's brother.
- Brother-in-law!

639
01:27:27,916 --> 01:27:29,957
Actually.

640
01:27:31,125 --> 01:27:34,832
And Judge Williams
will hear the trial in this very court.

641
01:27:35,000 --> 01:27:37,874
Judge Williams? Herod's brother.

642
01:27:38,041 --> 01:27:39,790
Whereas...

643
01:27:39,958 --> 01:27:43,332
Yes, and the King's brother.
He also administers illegal oaths.

644
01:27:43,500 --> 01:27:46,415
As the Grandmaster of the Orange Lodge.

645
01:27:46,583 --> 01:27:48,790
One law for the rich and another for the poor.

646
01:27:49,875 --> 01:27:53,499
The whole thing is a monstrous game,
a political box of tricks,

647
01:27:53,666 --> 01:27:56,290
with the cards stacked against innocent men.

648
01:27:57,333 --> 01:28:00,540
But there's one card left to be played.
Public opinion.

649
01:28:00,708 --> 01:28:04,082
You'd be well advised
to forget George Lovelace.

650
01:28:04,250 --> 01:28:06,207
And his kind.

651
01:28:06,375 --> 01:28:08,457
No-one wants to know them!

652
01:28:09,291 --> 01:28:11,540
And no-one will remember them!

653
01:28:11,708 --> 01:28:13,790
l'm terribly sorry.

654
01:28:16,166 --> 01:28:18,332
l'm afraid there's not much room.

655
01:28:18,500 --> 01:28:20,457
Ah... Oh, dear.

656
01:28:20,625 --> 01:28:22,582
lf you... Yes.

657
01:28:22,750 --> 01:28:24,999
That's all. l'm afraid the court is full.

658
01:28:25,166 --> 01:28:29,332
l'm terribly sorry, but the court is full.

659
01:28:48,333 --> 01:28:50,415
(Baby cries)

660
01:29:44,916 --> 01:29:46,999
(Whispering)

661
01:29:56,583 --> 01:29:58,665
(Whispering continues)

662
01:30:26,583 --> 01:30:28,665
(Muttering)

663
01:30:47,458 --> 01:30:49,540
(Weeping in background)

664
01:30:51,416 --> 01:30:54,332
What does trans...tr...

665
01:30:54,500 --> 01:30:56,457
Transportation.

666
01:30:56,625 --> 01:30:58,707
..mean?

667
01:30:59,583 --> 01:31:02,915
lt means they're going
a long way away on a boat.

668
01:31:14,541 --> 01:31:16,624
Seven years is a long time.

669
01:31:18,916 --> 01:31:20,999
l'm seven, aren't l?

670
01:32:02,166 --> 01:32:04,249
(Dog growling softly)

671
01:32:05,375 --> 01:32:07,457
Mr Frampton is not at home.

672
01:32:09,125 --> 01:32:11,207
When will he be back?

673
01:32:16,625 --> 01:32:18,707
l don't know.

674
01:32:42,500 --> 01:32:45,624
How l would love to visit Botany Bay.

675
01:32:45,791 --> 01:32:47,915
Have you read Cook?

676
01:32:49,000 --> 01:32:51,999
Readin' is for the leisured class.

677
01:32:57,250 --> 01:32:59,832
But when it falls into the wrong hands,

678
01:33:00,000 --> 01:33:02,082
it is a corrupter of morals.

679
01:33:03,166 --> 01:33:06,665
Strange chance that rabble-rouser Loveless
falling ill, what.

680
01:33:06,833 --> 01:33:11,957
Can't exercise his evil powers o?er
those gullible friends of his any more.

681
01:33:14,541 --> 01:33:19,165
Next thing we know, the wives
are going to be asking for parish relief.

682
01:33:19,333 --> 01:33:25,207
No family is entitled to relief if they can afford
to pay a shilling to join a union.

683
01:33:25,375 --> 01:33:28,874
Their leaders are simply
feathering their own nests.

684
01:33:29,041 --> 01:33:32,957
l wonder if he really is the ringleader.
Whether there aren't others, what.

685
01:33:33,125 --> 01:33:37,374
Some shadow puppet master up in London
manipulating him with rods.

686
01:33:37,541 --> 01:33:39,624
Pass.

687
01:33:43,500 --> 01:33:45,457
ln some strange way,

688
01:33:45,625 --> 01:33:47,707
l can't help respecting him.

689
01:33:49,208 --> 01:33:52,457
l can't quite put my finger on it.

690
01:33:55,791 --> 01:33:57,874
When all was lost,

691
01:33:59,666 --> 01:34:02,749
his eyes looked with such uncanniness.

692
01:34:04,333 --> 01:34:06,874
Almost as if he had won.

693
01:34:07,041 --> 01:34:09,290
Hurry along, Frampton.

694
01:34:31,625 --> 01:34:33,707
Good night, gentlemen.

695
01:36:04,125 --> 01:36:06,207
Bad books.

696
01:36:31,833 --> 01:36:34,540
lt's not the books that's bad, my cherub.

697
01:36:50,250 --> 01:37:09,540
(Chains rattling)

1
01:39:34,893 --> 01:39:36,975
Where's it coming from?

2
01:39:38,643 --> 01:39:43,017
I don't want anything that doesn't belong to me.
I couldn't touch it.

3
01:39:43,892 --> 01:39:46,599
Trust him, Betsy.

4
01:39:48,934 --> 01:39:51,933
It won't make up for what's happened.
But it'll help.

5
01:39:52,100 --> 01:39:56,891
It comes from London. People of all walks of life
are taking up our cause.

6
01:39:57,059 --> 01:40:00,181
Calling themselves
the London-Dorchester Committee.

7
01:40:00,348 --> 01:40:04,722
They've started a petition.
Meetings are being called all over the country.

8
01:40:04,890 --> 01:40:06,847
Questions in Parliament.

9
01:40:07,015 --> 01:40:10,431
They asked me to see
that you and the children don't go wanting.

10
01:40:12,182 --> 01:40:14,139
They want you to have it.

11
01:40:14,307 --> 01:40:16,805
It's a gift and it'll come every week.

12
01:40:17,889 --> 01:40:19,971
The Lord be praised.

13
01:40:28,264 --> 01:40:30,221
Hetty...

14
01:40:30,389 --> 01:40:32,470
Hetty!

15
01:40:35,721 --> 01:40:37,804
Oh, people are good.

16
01:41:35,717 --> 01:41:37,800
Are you up to walking, sir?

17
01:41:48,007 --> 01:41:50,089
I'm not likely to outdo you.

18
01:41:51,174 --> 01:41:54,672
We're having to bash through the town.
Let me remove them.

19
01:42:06,548 --> 01:42:08,422
It's all right.

20
01:42:09,381 --> 01:42:11,462
I'm not ashamed.

21
01:42:28,503 --> 01:42:31,335
We have injured no man's reputation,

22
01:42:31,503 --> 01:42:33,460
character,

23
01:42:33,628 --> 01:42:35,585
person,

24
01:42:35,753 --> 01:42:37,835
or property.

25
01:42:38,920 --> 01:42:41,585
We were uniting together to preserve ourselves,

26
01:42:41,753 --> 01:42:43,460
our wives,

27
01:42:43,628 --> 01:42:45,709
and our children...

28
01:42:46,752 --> 01:42:49,251
.. from utter degradation and starvation.

29
01:43:41,790 --> 01:43:43,664
(Horse-drawn vehicle passing)

30
01:44:33,411 --> 01:44:35,493
'God is our guide.

31
01:44:36,577 --> 01:44:38,535
From field, from wave,

32
01:44:38,702 --> 01:44:41,784
from plough, from anvil,

33
01:44:41,951 --> 01:44:44,034
and from loom.

34
01:44:45,118 --> 01:44:48,825
We come, our country's rights to save,

35
01:44:49,910 --> 01:44:53,117
and speak the tyrant faction's doom.

36
01:44:54,868 --> 01:44:58,407
We raise the watchword "liberty".

37
01:44:59,449 --> 01:45:03,907
We will, we will, we will be free. '

38
01:45:06,991 --> 01:45:09,073
'God is our guide.

39
01:45:10,158 --> 01:45:12,489
No swords we draw.

40
01:45:12,657 --> 01:45:19,156
We kindle not wars, battle fires.

41
01:45:20,240 --> 01:45:24,031
By reason, union, justice,

42
01:45:24,198 --> 01:45:26,281
laws,

43
01:45:27,365 --> 01:45:31,071
we claim the birthright of our sires.

44
01:45:32,364 --> 01:45:34,321
We raise the watchword "liberty".

45
01:45:34,489 --> 01:45:38,738
We will, we will, we will be free. '

46
01:45:46,112 --> 01:45:48,194
He meant this for you.

47
01:45:49,279 --> 01:45:51,236
And others like you.

48
01:45:51,404 --> 01:45:53,486
Not me.

49
01:45:55,070 --> 01:45:57,694
When you've done with it, don't throw it away.

50
01:45:58,779 --> 01:46:00,861
Let it go from hand to hand.

51
01:46:02,194 --> 01:46:04,902
My task is to teach the members of my class...

52
01:46:06,819 --> 01:46:11,985
.. that injustice cannot be allowed
to go unchallenged.

53
01:46:19,693 --> 01:46:21,776
Hello, Betsy.

54
01:47:40,686 --> 01:47:45,977
GEORGE: I thank you, my dear wife,
for the kind attention you've ever paid me.

55
01:47:47,186 --> 01:47:49,269
And you may safely rely on it,

56
01:47:50,436 --> 01:47:52,060
that as long as I live,

57
01:47:52,811 --> 01:47:56,019
it will be my constant endeavour
to return that kindness

58
01:47:56,185 --> 01:47:58,268
in every possible way.

59
01:47:59,352 --> 01:48:02,809
And that I shall never forget
the promise made at the altar.

60
01:48:05,060 --> 01:48:07,143
And though we may part awhile,

61
01:48:08,019 --> 01:48:10,559
I shall consider myself
under the same obligations

62
01:48:10,727 --> 01:48:13,224
as though living in your immediate presence.

63
01:48:15,100 --> 01:48:18,141
Be satisfied, my dear, on my account.

64
01:48:19,183 --> 01:48:21,432
Depend upon it.

65
01:48:21,600 --> 01:48:23,682
It will work together for good...

66
01:48:24,725 --> 01:48:26,807
.. and we shall yet rejoice together.

67
01:48:29,974 --> 01:48:32,056
I shall do well.

68
01:48:32,974 --> 01:48:35,765
For he who is the lord of the wind and waves...

69
01:48:36,849 --> 01:48:38,806
.. will be my support...

70
01:48:38,974 --> 01:48:41,056
in life...

71
01:48:42,057 --> 01:48:44,140
.. and death.

72
01:50:33,132 --> 01:50:36,381
For just one penny,
you can put the world in your pocket.

73
01:50:39,298 --> 01:50:41,379
Absolutely charming thing.

74
01:50:42,880 --> 01:50:45,504
- Nice journey, Captain.
- A profitable one.

75
01:50:46,713 --> 01:50:49,212
A pound a head it pays to keep the scum alive.

76
01:50:52,338 --> 01:50:53,879
British?

77
01:50:54,046 --> 01:50:56,129
Only the very best, my dear sir.

78
01:51:04,879 --> 01:51:06,044
Done.

79
01:51:06,212 --> 01:51:07,753
(Chuckles)

80
01:51:08,837 --> 01:51:10,919
(Piper plays in distance)

81
01:51:15,836 --> 01:51:17,918
d Barnacle Bill

82
01:51:26,294 --> 01:51:28,377
(Men shout encouragement)

83
01:51:35,376 --> 01:51:37,333
Come on, more!

84
01:51:37,501 --> 01:51:39,458
Into line, you lot.

85
01:51:39,626 --> 01:51:41,708
Come on!

86
01:51:44,042 --> 01:51:46,374
Name? Speak up, man.

87
01:51:46,541 --> 01:51:48,207
Neilson.

88
01:51:56,458 --> 01:51:58,624
OFFICER: Can we have a few more along?

89
01:52:00,750 --> 01:52:02,831
Hurry it up!

90
01:52:07,415 --> 01:52:08,414
Name?

91
01:52:08,582 --> 01:52:10,248
Blotters.

92
01:52:14,249 --> 01:52:15,789
Name?

93
01:52:15,957 --> 01:52:18,039
Loveless.

94
01:52:24,372 --> 01:52:26,454
(Fly buzzing)

95
01:52:31,913 --> 01:52:33,579
Next.

96
01:52:34,663 --> 01:52:36,786
- Where do I go?
- It's all there.

97
01:52:38,496 --> 01:52:41,620
OFFICER: Can we have a few more along,
please?

98
01:52:42,329 --> 01:52:44,286
Yes, but...

99
01:52:44,454 --> 01:52:46,411
where is it?

100
01:52:46,579 --> 01:52:48,661
That's for you to find out.

101
01:52:49,412 --> 01:52:50,953
Next.

102
01:52:51,121 --> 01:52:53,202
(Kookaburra laughs)

103
01:53:02,953 --> 01:53:04,910
About 300 miles.

104
01:53:05,078 --> 01:53:08,160
It should take you nine days,
a strong fellow like you.

105
01:53:08,328 --> 01:53:11,200
Don't eat your rations all at once or you'll starve.

106
01:53:11,368 --> 01:53:13,450
That way.

107
01:53:29,200 --> 01:53:31,157
BOY: Hey, mister!

108
01:53:31,325 --> 01:53:33,282
Could you help me?

109
01:53:33,450 --> 01:53:35,532
I don't know which way to go.

110
01:53:44,366 --> 01:53:46,323
Take it.

111
01:53:46,491 --> 01:53:54,406
Ta.

112
01:54:03,905 --> 01:54:04,946
Look.

113
01:54:05,655 --> 01:54:07,738
'C' stands for 'convict'.

114
01:54:08,697 --> 01:54:11,529
No... 'comrades'.

115
01:54:18,196 --> 01:54:20,153
What's your name?

116
01:54:20,321 --> 01:54:22,278
Charlie.

117
01:54:22,446 --> 01:54:24,403
Well, there you are, you see.

118
01:54:24,571 --> 01:54:26,528
Things are more than they appear.

119
01:54:26,696 --> 01:54:28,653
What's yours?

120
01:54:28,821 --> 01:54:30,777
Christopher.

121
01:54:30,945 --> 01:54:32,819
No, it isn't.

122
01:54:33,987 --> 01:54:35,444
(Bird squawks)

123
01:54:40,528 --> 01:54:42,194
Men are bad.

124
01:54:42,362 --> 01:54:44,361
Are you bad?

125
01:54:46,945 --> 01:54:49,025
So, not all men are bad.

126
01:54:50,568 --> 01:54:52,525
The truth is...

127
01:54:52,693 --> 01:54:54,775
that men are born good.

128
01:54:57,568 --> 01:54:59,650
Tell me...

129
01:55:00,860 --> 01:55:02,900
.. if we planted apples in this field,

130
01:55:03,068 --> 01:55:05,024
and the fruit grew rich and strong,

131
01:55:05,192 --> 01:55:07,149
and we planted apples in that field

132
01:55:07,317 --> 01:55:09,774
and the fruit didn't grow rich and strong...

133
01:55:09,942 --> 01:55:11,899
what's to blame?

134
01:55:12,067 --> 01:55:13,399
Hm?

135
01:55:13,567 --> 01:55:14,899
Well, go on.

136
01:55:15,067 --> 01:55:17,774
The apples what didn't come out right,
of course.

137
01:55:17,942 --> 01:55:19,274
No.

138
01:55:19,442 --> 01:55:22,857
We could have planted them here,
they'd have been all right.

139
01:55:23,024 --> 01:55:25,940
Some of them would have come out all right,
anyway.

140
01:55:26,858 --> 01:55:28,315
True.

141
01:55:29,274 --> 01:55:31,773
Some would survive in spite of everything.

142
01:55:34,816 --> 01:55:36,980
But we want them all to grow, don't we?

143
01:55:37,981 --> 01:55:40,021
You sound like a preacher.

144
01:55:40,189 --> 01:55:42,146
I'm sorry. I didn't mean to.

145
01:55:42,314 --> 01:55:44,188
It's OK.

146
01:55:44,897 --> 01:55:46,980
You don't look like one.

147
01:55:51,981 --> 01:55:54,062
(Horse's hooves approaching)

148
01:55:55,396 --> 01:55:57,354
Wait there. Don't move.

149
01:55:57,521 --> 01:55:59,604
We might be in luck here.

150
01:56:02,605 --> 01:56:03,520
Whoa!

151
01:56:03,688 --> 01:56:06,437
Sir! Whoa!

152
01:56:10,187 --> 01:56:12,269
I wonder if I might ask you a favour.

153
01:56:23,562 --> 01:56:25,311
We've got some papers.

154
01:56:25,479 --> 01:56:29,434
It's got a place name on it, but I don't know
because I'm new round here myself.

155
01:56:29,602 --> 01:56:31,142
I wonder if you could help him or...

156
01:56:31,310 --> 01:56:33,392
if you know where that is.

157
01:56:37,893 --> 01:56:40,684
Charlie, come here, quick!

158
01:56:53,684 --> 01:56:55,641
Right, get him up.

159
01:56:55,809 --> 01:56:58,433
Go on, Charlie, quickly. You're in luck, lad.

160
01:57:00,433 --> 01:57:01,974
Come on.

161
01:57:05,558 --> 01:57:07,307
Hold on.

162
01:57:07,475 --> 01:57:09,557
Fetch his pack, then.

163
01:57:17,223 --> 01:57:19,263
- Here you are, boy.
- Put it over your head.

164
01:57:19,431 --> 01:57:21,680
Thank you, ma'am. Bless you, boy.

165
01:58:15,094 --> 01:58:17,051
For what we're about to receive,

166
01:58:17,219 --> 01:58:19,301
may the Lord make us truly thankful.

167
01:58:20,260 --> 01:58:21,800
Amen.

168
01:59:50,752 --> 01:59:52,085
We will...

169
01:59:52,252 --> 01:59:54,335
(Voice echoes several times)

170
01:59:57,669 --> 01:59:59,625
.. be free!

171
01:59:59,793 --> 02:00:01,875
(Echoing)

172
02:00:07,126 --> 02:00:09,084
We will be free!

173
02:00:09,251 --> 02:00:11,334
(Echoing)

174
02:00:16,084 --> 02:00:18,166
(Insects chirrup and frogs croak)

175
02:00:23,459 --> 02:00:25,541
(Dingoes howl in distance)

176
02:00:48,248 --> 02:00:51,288
One, two! One, two!

177
02:00:51,456 --> 02:00:52,871
Keep together, you!

178
02:00:53,039 --> 02:00:55,746
One, two! One, two!

179
02:00:55,914 --> 02:00:59,621
One! Come on, you lazy shower of shits!

180
02:01:00,081 --> 02:01:01,830
Put some muscle into that.

181
02:01:01,997 --> 02:01:04,080
You want my boot up your arsehole?

182
02:01:04,622 --> 02:01:07,579
One, two! One, two!

183
02:01:07,746 --> 02:01:09,704
One, two!

184
02:01:09,871 --> 02:01:11,954
(Clattering of tools)

185
02:01:17,913 --> 02:01:19,995
If I catch any man shirking...

186
02:01:27,911 --> 02:01:29,868
And don't look at me like that.

187
02:01:30,036 --> 02:01:32,660
You'll be eating your own shit for breakfast.

188
02:01:34,578 --> 02:01:36,452
(Mutters)

189
02:01:39,452 --> 02:01:41,409
Stay. Stay, boy.

190
02:01:41,577 --> 02:01:43,451
Stay.

191
02:01:45,660 --> 02:01:48,159
Take it nice. There's a good boy. Take it nice.

192
02:01:48,327 --> 02:01:50,284
Come on, take it nice.

193
02:01:50,452 --> 02:01:52,909
Take it nice. Come on, take it nice.

194
02:01:53,077 --> 02:01:55,033
Take it... Aagh, you bastard!

195
02:01:55,201 --> 02:01:56,700
Bite me, would you?

196
02:01:56,867 --> 02:01:58,533
Bite me, you bastard?

197
02:02:03,992 --> 02:02:06,658
If I ever meet up with him back home,

198
02:02:07,409 --> 02:02:09,575
I'll show him where my foot will roam.

199
02:02:10,201 --> 02:02:12,281
It won't be where it ought to be,

200
02:02:13,282 --> 02:02:16,073
but up his arse and all for free.

201
02:02:22,449 --> 02:02:24,531
Keep up with us, Brine.

202
02:02:27,281 --> 02:02:29,863
Don't let this bastard road be our memorial.

203
02:03:06,653 --> 02:03:12,985
Water!

204
02:03:28,444 --> 02:03:30,109
Who shouted?

205
02:03:33,859 --> 02:03:35,567
He needs his boots.

206
02:03:40,901 --> 02:03:42,983
He says somebody stole 'em.

207
02:03:53,482 --> 02:03:55,565
Let him steal another pair.

208
02:04:10,231 --> 02:04:12,314
(Harmonica plays mournful tune)

209
02:05:02,394 --> 02:05:04,476
Are you all right there?

210
02:05:13,268 --> 02:05:15,350
(Drunken laughter)

211
02:05:22,601 --> 02:05:24,184
- Do you love me?
- Of course.

212
02:05:24,351 --> 02:05:26,017
- Do you love me?
- What do you think?

213
02:05:26,185 --> 02:05:29,015
- Do you? 'Cos I love you.
- You're a sight, mate.

214
02:05:29,183 --> 02:05:31,265
(Woman laughs)

215
02:05:41,349 --> 02:05:42,890
(Man shouts)

216
02:05:54,265 --> 02:05:56,222
You remind me of Ned Ludd.

217
02:05:56,390 --> 02:05:58,472
Who was he?

218
02:05:59,223 --> 02:06:02,013
He became a she
went he went machine-breaking.

219
02:06:06,681 --> 02:06:08,763
(Man and woman bickering)

220
02:06:26,220 --> 02:06:28,303
(Coins jangle)

221
02:06:34,803 --> 02:06:37,635
Ah... like a nice time, Bertie?

222
02:06:37,803 --> 02:06:39,760
(Chuckles)

223
02:06:39,928 --> 02:06:41,468
Huh?

224
02:06:41,636 --> 02:06:43,552
(Laughs drunkenly)

225
02:06:43,719 --> 02:06:45,927
There's not a man among you. (Cackles)

226
02:06:50,552 --> 02:06:52,634
Whatever you do, don't do it alone.

227
02:06:53,927 --> 02:06:56,134
One man is nothing. I've learned that.

228
02:06:57,218 --> 02:06:59,301
We're here to help each other.

229
02:07:06,427 --> 02:07:08,507
Go to sleep.

230
02:07:27,757 --> 02:07:28,798
Wait.

231
02:07:34,257 --> 02:07:36,339
How much?

232
02:07:45,214 --> 02:07:47,297
Too much.

233
02:08:06,837 --> 02:08:08,920
(Cicadas singing)

234
02:08:13,170 --> 02:08:14,752
(Grunts)

235
02:08:55,208 --> 02:08:57,291
Do you not like to be entertained?

236
02:09:20,331 --> 02:09:21,747
Hagh! Hagh! Hagh!

237
02:09:21,915 --> 02:09:24,664
Hagh! Hagh! Hagh! Hagh! Hagh!

238
02:09:25,790 --> 02:09:27,872
(Chuckles cockily)

239
02:09:30,998 --> 02:09:32,664
Yargh!

240
02:09:46,038 --> 02:09:47,995
What's this? What's this, eh?

241
02:09:48,163 --> 02:09:50,120
What's this?

242
02:09:50,288 --> 02:09:59,994
Look what I've got for you.

243
02:10:10,577 --> 02:10:12,243
Soldier.

244
02:10:14,952 --> 02:10:17,743
Come on, sweetie, come on. That's it. That's it.

245
02:10:49,741 --> 02:10:51,698
That's my boy.

246
02:10:51,866 --> 02:10:53,157
That's it.

247
02:11:01,698 --> 02:11:02,614
(Mouths)

248
02:11:02,782 --> 02:11:05,156
Good dog! Good boy, good soldier.

249
02:11:05,323 --> 02:11:06,947
Good soldier.

250
02:12:50,940 --> 02:12:53,521
If you dig any deeper, you'll reach England.

251
02:12:54,605 --> 02:12:56,187
(Laughs)

252
02:13:07,063 --> 02:13:09,145
MAN: You there!

253
02:13:16,604 --> 02:13:18,478
Yes, you!

254
02:13:19,396 --> 02:13:22,061
Not you, you imbecile!

255
02:13:22,854 --> 02:13:25,560
Don't they understand the plain English?

256
02:13:29,895 --> 02:13:32,644
Our Father, which art in heaven

257
02:13:34,186 --> 02:13:36,144
Hallowed be Thy name

258
02:13:36,311 --> 02:13:38,269
Thy kingdom come

259
02:13:38,436 --> 02:13:41,517
Thy will be done, on earth as it is in heaven

260
02:13:42,643 --> 02:13:44,725
Give us this day our daily bread

261
02:13:45,601 --> 02:13:48,600
And forgive us our debts,
as we forgive our debtors

262
02:13:50,809 --> 02:13:52,767
Lead us not into temptation

263
02:13:52,934 --> 02:13:55,017
But deliver us from evil

264
02:13:57,392 --> 02:13:59,474
Amen.

265
02:15:12,428 --> 02:15:16,594
Tell me something more about yourself
for identification, monsieur.

266
02:15:18,845 --> 02:15:20,925
I was born William Moncrieff Norfolk,

267
02:15:21,093 --> 02:15:23,175
New Year's Day in the year 1790.

268
02:15:23,843 --> 02:15:25,800
Educated at Harrow and Oxford.

269
02:15:25,968 --> 02:15:27,925
Commanded a regiment at Waterloo.

270
02:15:28,093 --> 02:15:30,050
Great times. (Clears throat)

271
02:15:30,218 --> 02:15:33,842
I came to New South Wales
as governor of this province.

272
02:15:35,135 --> 02:15:37,508
My wife finds the climate here oppressive,

273
02:15:37,675 --> 02:15:39,466
suffers from the vapours.

274
02:15:39,634 --> 02:15:41,383
Longs to go back to Grantham.

275
02:15:41,550 --> 02:15:44,674
Pines pathetically for the values
of the mother country.

276
02:15:44,842 --> 02:15:49,508
Women are happier at home, of course.
They shouldn't meddle in the outside world.

277
02:15:49,675 --> 02:15:52,507
Our daughter, Flower,
has adapted rather better.

278
02:15:52,674 --> 02:15:54,423
She's taken to horses.

279
02:15:54,591 --> 02:15:57,090
She'll make an excellent marriage one day.

280
02:15:59,591 --> 02:16:02,298
I sometimes feel the urge
to have more children -

281
02:16:02,466 --> 02:16:04,215
a son.

282
02:16:04,383 --> 02:16:06,465
But my wife and I...

283
02:16:08,466 --> 02:16:10,630
It's like a square peg in a round hole.

284
02:16:11,797 --> 02:16:13,671
(Norfolk sighs)

285
02:16:14,547 --> 02:16:17,796
Now I regard the subjects of this province
as my family.

286
02:16:18,506 --> 02:16:20,671
I'm a martyr to duty, public service,

287
02:16:21,381 --> 02:16:22,713
diplomacy.

288
02:16:22,881 --> 02:16:26,337
It's generally acknowledged
I have promoted a measure of stability

289
02:16:26,505 --> 02:16:28,212
where before there was none.

290
02:16:28,380 --> 02:16:30,462
Merci, monsieur.

291
02:16:31,338 --> 02:16:34,462
It is obvious you possess
a very liberal turn of mind,

292
02:16:35,171 --> 02:16:38,170
a quality that is greatly appreciated
in my country.

293
02:16:38,338 --> 02:16:43,128
You will of course be familiar with
les raisons d'tre of the French Revolution:

294
02:16:43,295 --> 02:16:48,461
libert, galit, fraternit.

295
02:16:57,462 --> 02:16:58,876
Your aperitive, sir.

296
02:16:59,043 --> 02:17:00,834
Apritif!

297
02:17:01,002 --> 02:17:03,084
Sacr bleu!

298
02:17:11,168 --> 02:17:14,501
Tell me another one of your wonderful stories,
Stanfield.

299
02:17:14,667 --> 02:17:16,625
I don't think I know any more.

300
02:17:16,792 --> 02:17:19,416
But you must! You promised me!

301
02:17:19,584 --> 02:17:21,666
I know you were only pretending.

302
02:17:34,375 --> 02:17:36,749
I don't always understand what Jesus says.

303
02:17:36,916 --> 02:17:38,749
Do you?

304
02:17:38,916 --> 02:17:43,665
If Papa said such things, he would become
a laughing stock, wouldn't he?

305
02:17:45,208 --> 02:17:47,290
I have a daughter...

306
02:17:48,373 --> 02:17:50,455
.. just about your age.

307
02:17:55,831 --> 02:17:57,705
Don't forget to clean my shoes.

308
02:18:13,622 --> 02:18:15,704
You must learn to read,

309
02:18:16,663 --> 02:18:18,121
to write,

310
02:18:18,288 --> 02:18:20,370
and think for yourselves.

311
02:18:24,037 --> 02:18:26,120
You must use this...

312
02:18:27,412 --> 02:18:29,495
.. not this.

313
02:18:32,537 --> 02:18:35,245
If we fight amongst ourselves,

314
02:18:35,412 --> 02:18:38,118
we perpetuate our serfdom...

315
02:18:41,660 --> 02:18:45,493
.. because they know
we will never stand together against them.

316
02:18:48,785 --> 02:18:52,618
You're becoming quite famous, Mr Stanfield,
quite the celebrity.

317
02:18:52,785 --> 02:18:55,658
People in high places
are championing your cause.

318
02:18:55,826 --> 02:18:57,908
I envy you.

319
02:18:58,659 --> 02:19:00,742
You should read about yourself.

320
02:19:11,242 --> 02:19:12,657
Tell me...

321
02:19:14,325 --> 02:19:16,282
.. what is this Society of Friends,

322
02:19:16,450 --> 02:19:20,407
the wisdom of which you are so eager
to bestow on others?

323
02:19:21,367 --> 02:19:25,199
To whom, I may say, I've already extended
the hand of friendship.

324
02:19:29,073 --> 02:19:31,280
Perhaps you could wish to share it with me?

325
02:19:32,365 --> 02:19:34,447
I am, as you know,

326
02:19:35,323 --> 02:19:37,614
as indeed all must know, a fair man.

327
02:19:39,115 --> 02:19:42,322
Why, I'm willing to talk to anyone
who'll listen to me.

328
02:19:48,072 --> 02:19:50,154
You won't read about yourself?

329
02:19:53,822 --> 02:19:55,904
You should.

330
02:20:05,946 --> 02:20:07,903
Mr Stanfield...

331
02:20:08,071 --> 02:20:10,153
we are not uneducated men, are we?

332
02:20:12,696 --> 02:20:14,778
The field was my university.

333
02:20:19,152 --> 02:20:22,610
Stanfield, I respect your homespun philosophy.

334
02:20:23,319 --> 02:20:26,026
But I cannot have you preaching insurrection.

335
02:20:29,152 --> 02:20:32,150
The native population
are little more than savages,

336
02:20:32,318 --> 02:20:35,734
in spite of my efforts to rescue them
from extinction.

337
02:20:36,610 --> 02:20:39,942
Surely you must realise the impropriety of er...

338
02:20:42,568 --> 02:20:44,525
.. arousing them?

339
02:20:46,985 --> 02:20:49,566
I know that we are all God's children.

340
02:20:54,275 --> 02:20:56,233
You imbecile!

341
02:20:56,400 --> 02:20:58,649
You snivelling workhouse guttersnipe!

342
02:20:58,817 --> 02:21:00,191
How dare you?

343
02:21:00,359 --> 02:21:03,983
How dare you fetch your filthy stench
to foul the air?

344
02:21:04,150 --> 02:21:06,106
You contaminating labouring scab!

345
02:21:06,273 --> 02:21:08,231
Get out!

346
02:21:08,398 --> 02:21:12,481
Get out, before I send you back
where you belong, inside your whore's belly!

347
02:21:23,106 --> 02:21:24,980
(Sobs)

348
02:21:58,228 --> 02:21:59,685
(Branches crack)

349
02:22:07,269 --> 02:22:09,143
Hurry?

350
02:22:09,811 --> 02:22:14,142
Well, I was beginning to think there were
no more people living in the world.

351
02:22:14,310 --> 02:22:16,809
You're the first person I've seen in a week.

352
02:22:20,185 --> 02:22:22,976
I'm making for the Governor's
country residence.

353
02:22:26,227 --> 02:22:28,225
Have you got anything to eat?

354
02:22:31,184 --> 02:22:32,516
Here.

355
02:22:34,392 --> 02:22:36,058
See for yourself.

356
02:22:40,809 --> 02:22:42,891
You want to go that way.

357
02:22:46,015 --> 02:22:47,973
Which way are you going?

358
02:22:48,140 --> 02:22:50,098
That way.

359
02:22:50,265 --> 02:22:52,223
Where have you come from?

360
02:22:52,390 --> 02:22:54,473
That way.

361
02:23:09,473 --> 02:23:11,555
Why are you going so fast?

362
02:23:12,264 --> 02:23:14,347
You want to get there, don't you?

363
02:23:16,180 --> 02:23:18,262
I'm going to see my father.

364
02:23:19,055 --> 02:23:21,012
I haven't seen him in three years.

365
02:23:21,180 --> 02:23:23,262
(Charlie moans softly)

366
02:23:24,138 --> 02:23:26,221
Hey, don't fret now.

367
02:23:27,305 --> 02:23:29,512
We'll find something to eat tomorrow.

368
02:23:33,303 --> 02:23:35,385
You know, when I get home...

369
02:23:37,428 --> 02:23:40,010
.. I'll not go hungry again, that's for sure.

370
02:23:42,761 --> 02:23:44,844
I'll forget about this place.

371
02:23:47,261 --> 02:23:50,176
No child of mine will know
what I've been through.

372
02:23:53,469 --> 02:23:55,551
Now, if I was the Lord Mayor...

373
02:23:58,469 --> 02:24:00,551
.. I'd get rid of the old way of life.

374
02:24:04,135 --> 02:24:06,425
There'd be no more bowing and scraping.

375
02:24:09,676 --> 02:24:11,758
I'd build a new world.

376
02:24:14,509 --> 02:24:16,467
Do you hear me, Charlie?

377
02:24:16,634 --> 02:24:18,717
(Charlie snores)

378
02:24:22,216 --> 02:24:24,298
Oh, well.

379
02:24:34,466 --> 02:24:35,506
Look!

380
02:24:41,798 --> 02:24:43,880
Oh, it's beautiful.

381
02:24:44,965 --> 02:24:47,047
- Good?
- Mm.

382
02:24:52,256 --> 02:24:54,755
See them up there? They're the biggest.

383
02:24:54,922 --> 02:24:57,004
That's the boy. A few more.

384
02:24:58,255 --> 02:25:00,338
That's good.

385
02:25:53,126 --> 02:25:54,959
Charlie!

386
02:26:31,873 --> 02:26:43,830
Charlie?

387
02:28:28,529 --> 02:28:30,611
(Shrill whistle)

388
02:28:31,696 --> 02:28:33,653
Come here! Come!

389
02:28:33,821 --> 02:28:35,903
Bring 'em round. Bring 'em back.

390
02:28:38,446 --> 02:28:40,528
(Whistling and sheep bleating)

391
02:28:43,654 --> 02:28:45,985
Come on! Go! Turn 'em round!

392
02:28:46,153 --> 02:28:48,235
Bring 'em back.

393
02:29:02,319 --> 02:29:04,276
- Good night, ma'am.
- Good night.

394
02:29:04,444 --> 02:29:06,401
- Good day's work, yeah?
- It was.

395
02:29:06,569 --> 02:29:08,651
(Plays tune)

396
02:30:01,356 --> 02:30:03,564
Are we saying good night, then, ma'am?

397
02:30:16,354 --> 02:30:19,270
Tell me, James,
are you happy here working for me?

398
02:30:20,771 --> 02:30:22,312
Yes.

399
02:30:22,479 --> 02:30:24,519
I've been happy enough, Mrs Carlyle.

400
02:30:24,687 --> 02:30:26,769
Mrs Carlyle!

401
02:30:27,853 --> 02:30:29,352
Mrs Carlyle.

402
02:30:29,520 --> 02:30:31,477
My name's Violet.

403
02:30:31,645 --> 02:30:33,727
Yes, ma'am.

404
02:30:44,102 --> 02:30:46,268
Do you know, ever since my husband...

405
02:30:47,602 --> 02:30:50,726
Do you know, I've never heard my name
for three whole years?

406
02:30:50,894 --> 02:30:53,018
I was prepared to think I never had one.

407
02:31:13,683 --> 02:31:17,348
Have you ever thought, James,
to make yourself a life out here?

408
02:31:18,266 --> 02:31:21,515
I mean, this country has a lot to offer
for a man like you.

409
02:31:22,391 --> 02:31:24,598
How should I have managed without you?

410
02:31:25,558 --> 02:31:28,432
I could see to it that you had every opportunity.

411
02:31:28,599 --> 02:31:32,181
I could arrange for your wife and your children
to come and join you.

412
02:31:32,348 --> 02:31:34,389
I'm childless.

413
02:31:35,098 --> 02:31:37,931
Ah, it's terrible to be alone with oneself.

414
02:31:39,307 --> 02:31:42,639
I do wish you'd consider it.
I'm not getting any younger.

415
02:31:48,221 --> 02:31:50,054
I love my wife.

416
02:32:01,513 --> 02:32:03,594
(Beckons and clicks tongue)

417
02:32:22,469 --> 02:32:24,427
I'm sorry to lose you.

418
02:32:24,594 --> 02:32:26,677
This is from your brother.

419
02:32:28,178 --> 02:32:30,052
George?

420
02:32:46,509 --> 02:32:48,466
'My dearest brother,

421
02:32:48,634 --> 02:32:52,215
I pray to God my message reaches you at last.

422
02:32:52,383 --> 02:32:54,340
I've tried all manner of means,

423
02:32:54,508 --> 02:32:57,632
but hearing nothing from you,
I've feared the worst.

424
02:32:59,258 --> 02:33:03,257
It gladdens my heart to alert you
to the news of our freedom.

425
02:33:04,050 --> 02:33:06,715
The Good Lord has looked into
the hearts of men,

426
02:33:06,883 --> 02:33:09,256
and shown them that, imperfect as we are,

427
02:33:09,965 --> 02:33:13,714
we did never countenance violence
nor any violation of the law.

428
02:33:14,590 --> 02:33:20,298
Good friends at home have rallied to our cause
and argued long and hard on our behalf.

429
02:33:22,674 --> 02:33:26,421
Rejoice, my long lost brother,
in the free pardon granted to us.

430
02:33:27,630 --> 02:33:31,379
See to it that you complete your work
to the best of your ability,

431
02:33:32,255 --> 02:33:35,171
that our time here
may be said to be honestly done.

432
02:33:35,922 --> 02:33:38,129
We shall all be waiting to welcome you,

433
02:33:38,838 --> 02:33:41,211
all save Hammett, of whom there is no trace.

434
02:33:41,379 --> 02:33:43,336
Fear not, brother.

435
02:33:43,504 --> 02:33:47,461
He that is for us
is more than all that is against us.

436
02:33:48,254 --> 02:33:50,336
We will, we will be free.

437
02:33:52,046 --> 02:33:54,003
Your ever loving brother,

438
02:33:54,171 --> 02:33:56,253
George Loveless. '

439
02:34:14,918 --> 02:34:17,000
(Sings to himself)

440
02:34:18,334 --> 02:34:20,667
Come on. That's good.

441
02:34:27,793 --> 02:34:29,750
Ah, s, s.

442
02:34:29,918 --> 02:34:31,874
S, bella, bella.

443
02:34:32,042 --> 02:34:34,874
(Chuckles) Bella. Bellissima!

444
02:34:36,875 --> 02:34:38,832
No touch.

445
02:34:39,000 --> 02:34:40,957
It's very hot, you understand?

446
02:34:41,125 --> 02:34:42,874
It's hot, it's... (Sizzles)

447
02:34:43,042 --> 02:34:44,999
Ah, hot! Caldo. Molto caldo.

448
02:34:45,167 --> 02:34:47,123
No touch, no. You come with me.

449
02:34:47,291 --> 02:34:49,248
I take your image.

450
02:34:49,416 --> 02:34:51,540
I take image of you.

451
02:34:51,707 --> 02:34:53,873
You understand? Come, come. I show you.

452
02:34:54,041 --> 02:34:55,998
I show you.

453
02:34:56,166 --> 02:34:58,206
Standing here. Standing very still.

454
02:34:58,374 --> 02:35:00,331
Like so. Very still.

455
02:35:00,499 --> 02:35:02,456
You stand. Good.

456
02:35:02,624 --> 02:35:04,579
Yeah, very good. Very good.

457
02:35:04,747 --> 02:35:06,704
Stand here, very still.

458
02:35:06,872 --> 02:35:08,663
Good, good, good.

459
02:35:08,830 --> 02:35:09,746
(Chuckles)

460
02:35:09,914 --> 02:35:11,871
Molto, molto bene!

461
02:35:12,039 --> 02:35:14,121
Mwah! Mwah! (Chuckles)

462
02:35:16,289 --> 02:35:19,121
Oh, it's so good. Don't move!

463
02:35:45,537 --> 02:35:47,494
Ges bambino!

464
02:35:47,662 --> 02:35:49,536
Madonna di Dio! Hey!

465
02:35:50,162 --> 02:35:51,827
Get a... Get away!

466
02:35:51,995 --> 02:35:53,950
You get a... Go away!

467
02:35:54,118 --> 02:35:56,742
Go away! Va via! Move! Move!

468
02:35:56,910 --> 02:35:57,950
Move!

469
02:36:00,535 --> 02:36:02,492
No, no, no. Mo?e, mo?e!

470
02:36:02,660 --> 02:36:04,117
No, no, no, no!

471
02:36:04,285 --> 02:36:05,450
Stay still.

472
02:36:05,618 --> 02:36:07,950
No, you, get away! Get...

473
02:36:08,118 --> 02:36:10,074
Oh, mamma mia!

474
02:36:10,242 --> 02:36:12,658
You, stay, but you, move!

475
02:36:13,950 --> 02:36:16,033
Stay very still!

476
02:36:17,367 --> 02:36:20,324
Dieci, nove, otto, sette,

477
02:36:21,200 --> 02:36:24,491
sei, cinque, quattro, tre,

478
02:36:24,659 --> 02:36:26,532
due, uno!

479
02:36:46,781 --> 02:36:48,738
(Tinkling)

480
02:36:48,906 --> 02:36:50,988
(Whistles)

481
02:37:17,237 --> 02:37:19,111
Hammett!

482
02:37:22,237 --> 02:37:25,986
Ges!

483
02:37:26,154 --> 02:37:28,111
(Clattering)

484
02:37:28,279 --> 02:37:30,236
(Wails)

485
02:37:30,404 --> 02:37:32,484
(Mutters angrily)

486
02:37:35,235 --> 02:37:36,984
What do you do?

487
02:37:37,152 --> 02:37:38,942
You destroy my work!

488
02:37:39,110 --> 02:37:41,192
(Wails)

489
02:37:42,110 --> 02:37:43,859
Idiota!

490
02:37:44,027 --> 02:37:46,109
(Photographer sobs)

491
02:38:57,021 --> 02:38:58,895
(Cackles)

492
02:39:02,104 --> 02:39:04,186
(Audience gasps)

493
02:39:13,894 --> 02:39:15,559
(Cackles)

494
02:39:20,352 --> 02:39:23,726
AUCTIONEER: Magnificent creature,
ladies and gentlemen.

495
02:39:23,894 --> 02:39:27,017
Feast yourself on that gleaming, naked flesh -

496
02:39:27,184 --> 02:39:30,975
the arms... made for lifting heavy loads,

497
02:39:31,143 --> 02:39:34,100
the back, like a mule.

498
02:39:34,268 --> 02:39:35,808
Come now, ladies and gentlemen.

499
02:39:35,976 --> 02:39:39,683
You all look as if you could do with
a little domestic assistance.

500
02:39:39,851 --> 02:39:41,183
(Ribald laughter)

501
02:39:41,351 --> 02:39:43,307
The torso, ladies and gentlemen.

502
02:39:43,475 --> 02:39:45,432
The biceps!

503
02:39:45,600 --> 02:39:49,891
Ah, ladies and gentlemen,
what am I bid for this fine human specimen?

504
02:39:50,058 --> 02:39:52,016
What am I bid?

505
02:39:52,183 --> 02:39:55,641
He may be a bit rough and ready,
but treat him right, I say,

506
02:39:55,808 --> 02:39:58,099
and there's a hard day's work in him yet.

507
02:39:59,973 --> 02:40:02,930
I want to hear the sound of money,
ladies and gentlemen.

508
02:40:03,098 --> 02:40:04,639
Four shillings.

509
02:40:04,806 --> 02:40:06,764
Now, there's a lady of measure.

510
02:40:06,931 --> 02:40:09,014
FOP: Five shillings.

511
02:40:10,140 --> 02:40:12,097
WOMAN. Six shillings.

512
02:40:12,265 --> 02:40:14,222
FOP: Seven shillings.

513
02:40:14,390 --> 02:40:15,929
WOMAN: Eight shillings.

514
02:40:16,097 --> 02:40:17,804
FOP: Nine shillings.

515
02:40:17,972 --> 02:40:21,513
Dig deep into your pockets.
I want to hear the jingle of coin.

516
02:40:22,847 --> 02:40:25,596
Is there any advance on 17 shillings?

517
02:40:29,180 --> 02:40:31,263
FOP: 18.

518
02:40:33,138 --> 02:40:34,595
19.

519
02:40:34,763 --> 02:40:38,137
Do I hear a pound?
Will anyone give me a round pound?

520
02:40:38,304 --> 02:40:40,803
Look at the muscles, ladies and gentlemen.

521
02:40:45,513 --> 02:40:46,845
One pound.

522
02:40:47,013 --> 02:40:48,968
Going, for a pound.

523
02:40:49,136 --> 02:40:50,760
Going, going...

524
02:40:50,927 --> 02:40:53,176
gone for a pound!

525
02:40:53,344 --> 02:40:55,426
Thank you, sir.

526
02:41:33,842 --> 02:41:35,424
Jump!

527
02:41:56,256 --> 02:41:58,338
(Whispers)

528
02:42:16,963 --> 02:42:18,920
The bastard.

529
02:42:19,088 --> 02:42:21,045
He won't lick me.

530
02:42:21,213 --> 02:42:23,295
I'll see him in hell first.

531
02:42:28,336 --> 02:42:30,502
So how's it feel to join the nobility?

532
02:42:34,378 --> 02:42:37,668
If you were old enough to know better,
I'd chop your balls off.

533
02:42:41,294 --> 02:42:43,376
There's one thing you don't do, son.

534
02:42:44,877 --> 02:42:47,084
And that's turn against your own kind.

535
02:42:56,002 --> 02:43:00,041
There's some folk that think
they're better than others. They're not.

536
02:43:00,209 --> 02:43:02,500
They're just more selfish, that's all.

537
02:43:04,209 --> 02:43:06,291
What's your name?

538
02:43:07,292 --> 02:43:09,250
Out here, I have no name.

539
02:43:09,417 --> 02:43:10,958
Why are you here?

540
02:43:13,417 --> 02:43:15,500
I'm here instead of my brother.

541
02:43:17,499 --> 02:43:20,081
What's the difference? We're all brothers.

542
02:43:22,582 --> 02:43:24,539
What did your brother do?

543
02:43:24,707 --> 02:43:26,789
He's a carpenter, a craftsman.

544
02:43:28,540 --> 02:43:30,623
If it wasn't for him and others like him,

545
02:43:30,790 --> 02:43:33,080
then everything would just fall apart.

546
02:43:41,373 --> 02:43:43,455
I mean, what crime did he commit?

547
02:43:52,080 --> 02:43:53,746
Him?

548
02:43:54,497 --> 02:43:56,579
Oh, he didn't do anything wrong.

549
02:43:57,330 --> 02:43:59,412
He just wanted to see folks treated right.

550
02:44:01,372 --> 02:44:03,454
He believed in what he was doing.

551
02:44:05,911 --> 02:44:09,285
And out there, there are five others just like him.

552
02:44:12,120 --> 02:44:15,327
Now that I know what they've been through,
I admire them.

553
02:44:15,495 --> 02:44:17,577
I count myself one of them.

554
02:44:33,994 --> 02:44:36,409
All my life, people thought they owned me.

555
02:44:37,910 --> 02:44:39,992
But I'm a free man.

556
02:44:41,701 --> 02:44:43,783
In here, where it counts,

557
02:44:44,618 --> 02:44:46,700
I am a free man.

558
02:44:49,493 --> 02:44:51,658
No matter how other men may treat you,

559
02:44:52,701 --> 02:44:54,781
they can never own your soul.

560
02:44:59,241 --> 02:45:01,323
Remember that.

561
02:45:26,031 --> 02:45:27,571
Push!

562
02:46:48,983 --> 02:46:50,272
Run!

563
02:47:01,773 --> 02:47:02,814
Jump!

564
02:47:14,564 --> 02:47:15,980
Agh!

565
02:47:16,772 --> 02:47:18,855
CHARLIE: Help!

566
02:47:20,522 --> 02:47:21,980
Help!

567
02:47:22,147 --> 02:47:24,103
(Men laugh)

568
02:47:24,270 --> 02:47:32,686
Help!

569
02:47:35,145 --> 02:47:36,686
Get down here.

570
02:47:36,854 --> 02:47:40,435
You are a very silly young man.

571
02:47:40,603 --> 02:47:42,685
Come on, run. Run.

572
02:48:14,558 --> 02:48:16,515
So, comrade...

573
02:48:16,683 --> 02:48:19,515
are you going to tell us your name,
or aren't you?

574
02:48:25,683 --> 02:48:28,514
Are you going to tell us your name,
or aren't you?

575
02:48:39,140 --> 02:48:41,223
Free man.

576
02:48:44,265 --> 02:48:46,347
My name...

577
02:48:47,431 --> 02:48:49,513
.. is Adam Freeman.

578
02:48:50,264 --> 02:48:52,347
(Heavy thud)

579
02:48:55,306 --> 02:48:58,013
Now, you just sign this transportation order.

580
02:48:59,139 --> 02:49:01,220
I'll give you a receipt.

581
02:49:04,971 --> 02:49:08,511
He'll be sent to the penal settlement
at Norfolk Island...

582
02:49:10,054 --> 02:49:12,345
.. the dwelling of devils in human form,

583
02:49:13,179 --> 02:49:15,261
and refuse of Botany Bay,

584
02:49:16,346 --> 02:49:18,427
doubly damned.

585
02:49:21,553 --> 02:49:23,635
He'd be better off dead.

586
02:49:45,385 --> 02:49:47,468
(Thunder cracks)

587
02:50:33,423 --> 02:50:35,505
(Audience whistles and claps)

588
02:50:36,798 --> 02:50:38,672
(Cheering)

589
02:50:56,878 --> 02:51:03,502
Ladies and gentlemen, it is my privilege
to stand here as a representative of you all -

590
02:51:05,003 --> 02:51:09,211
many thousands of men and women
from all parts of the country...

591
02:51:10,128 --> 02:51:14,501
.. whose prayers and entreaties
and remonstrances...

592
02:51:15,544 --> 02:51:19,918
.. have brought about the return
of these ill-used men.

593
02:51:20,086 --> 02:51:22,168
(Applause)

594
02:51:23,669 --> 02:51:25,210
And...

595
02:51:25,377 --> 02:51:27,460
And have supported their families...

596
02:51:28,252 --> 02:51:30,416
.. during their long and arduous exile.

597
02:51:31,167 --> 02:51:33,041
(Cheering)

598
02:51:35,792 --> 02:51:40,249
I do not have to remind you that the women
have suffered along with their men.

599
02:51:43,334 --> 02:51:45,790
We shall not forget the authors and abettors

600
02:51:45,958 --> 02:51:49,707
of this cruel and vindictive violation
of the laws of humanity.

601
02:51:50,416 --> 02:51:54,248
Most truly, those men have earned
for themselves an ignoble fame.

602
02:51:54,416 --> 02:51:58,873
But my task today is to praise and thank
those others who have helped our cause.

603
02:51:59,041 --> 02:52:01,332
(Crowd shouts out names)
Robert Owen! Cobbett!

604
02:52:01,499 --> 02:52:04,622
Grantwell! Whitley! Moore and Pitt!

605
02:52:04,790 --> 02:52:06,872
(Pitt chuckles) Yes.

606
02:52:07,665 --> 02:52:12,539
But see who have really lent their weight
to these joint efforts.

607
02:52:12,707 --> 02:52:14,664
The silk weavers,

608
02:52:14,832 --> 02:52:16,372
shipwrights,

609
02:52:16,540 --> 02:52:18,204
- joiners...
- Trimmers!

610
02:52:18,371 --> 02:52:20,329
- .. cordwainers...
- Blacksmiths!

611
02:52:20,496 --> 02:52:22,662
- .. journeymen tailors...
- Whitesmiths!

612
02:52:22,830 --> 02:52:24,579
- .. hatters...
- Brassmakers!

613
02:52:24,746 --> 02:52:26,829
- .. corkers...
- Tin-plate workers.

614
02:52:26,996 --> 02:52:28,954
- Bricklayers!
- Blacksmiths!

615
02:52:29,121 --> 02:52:31,079
Glass-blowers!

616
02:52:31,246 --> 02:52:33,204
- Trimmers!
- Wheelers!

617
02:52:33,371 --> 02:52:34,287
Brassmakers!

618
02:52:34,455 --> 02:52:35,994
Yes, yes, yes.

619
02:52:36,162 --> 02:52:38,119
Paper stainers, coach painters...

620
02:52:38,287 --> 02:52:39,411
Gardeners!

621
02:52:39,579 --> 02:52:41,536
.. and gardeners.

622
02:52:41,704 --> 02:52:45,286
To all of you, our heartfelt thanks.

623
02:52:45,454 --> 02:52:46,786
(Applause)

624
02:52:46,954 --> 02:52:48,911
And finally, ladies and gentlemen,

625
02:52:49,079 --> 02:52:52,035
let us thank our friend the lanternist,

626
02:52:52,203 --> 02:52:56,035
who, through the power of optics
and its magical transformations,

627
02:52:56,203 --> 02:52:58,285
has told the story here today.

628
02:52:59,078 --> 02:53:02,702
It was almost as though he had been
present throughout himself.

629
02:53:02,869 --> 02:53:03,785
(Applause)

630
02:53:03,953 --> 02:53:06,827
Ars magna lucis et umbrae.

631
02:53:10,242 --> 02:53:11,283
George.

632
02:53:14,451 --> 02:53:16,533
